  "prompt": "How many books does an average person read in a year?",
  "response": "The number of books an average person reads in a year can vary significantly based on factors such as country, age, education level, and personal interests. However, based on available data from recent surveys and studies:\n\n- **United States:** According to a 2021 Pew Research Center survey, the median number of books read by American adults is approximately **12 books per year**. This means that half of the respondents read more than 12 books, while the other half read fewer.\n\n- **United Kingdom:** Similar trends are observed in the UK, where surveys suggest that the average adult reads around **10-12 books annually**.\n\n- **Global Perspective:** Globally, the average number may differ widely due to variations in access to books, literacy rates, and cultural emphasis on reading. In many countries with lower literacy rates or limited access to books, the average number of books read per person annually is likely lower.\n\n**Additional Considerations:**\n\n1. **Demographics:** Younger people, particularly those in higher education, tend to read more books annually compared to older demographics.\n\n2. **Access to Technology:** The rise of e-books and audiobooks has made reading more accessible, potentially increasing the number of books people consume.\n\n3. **Cultural Factors:** In cultures where reading is highly valued and integrated into daily life, individuals may read more books on average.\n\n4. **Personal Habits:** Individual reading habits vary widely. Some people may read multiple books per month, while others may read sporadically.\n\n**Conclusion:**\n\nWhile the average number of books read per person each year is often cited to be around **10-15 books** in many developed countries, this number can fluctuate based on various factors. It's also important to recognize that reading habits are highly personal and can vary widely from one individual to another.",
